{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480249"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:40:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:40:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"32"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/32"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.07,0.06,0.07,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"32"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/32"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"32"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76127"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4853"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44913"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents with a six month history of increasing difficulty with her hearing. She struggles to hear individual conversations at family events where there is \u0027quite a lot of noise.\u0027 She denies any vertigo, tinnitus, or motion sickness. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Her current medications include metformin and atenolol. She does not have any allergies. On clinical examination, Rinne\u0027s test demonstrates air conduction better than bone conduction in both ears. Weber\u0027s test is conducted, with sound louder in the right ear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the cause of her hearing impairment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sensorineural deafness in both ears, worse on the right","Conductive deafness in both ears, worse on the left","Conductive deafness of right ear, sensorineural deafness on left","Conductive deafness in both ears, worse on the right","Sensorineural deafness in both ears, worse on the left"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presbycusis, a term used to describe age-related sensorineural hearing loss. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn the Rinne\u0027s test, sensorineural deafness will cause air and bone conduction to be reduced equally. Therefore, air conduction is better than bone conduction and Rinne\u0027s test will be positive as is normal. Conductive deafness will lead to no note being audible at the external meatus and hence Rinne\u0027s negative. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn the Weber\u0027s test, sensorineural deafness will cause sound to be perceived better in the normal ear while conductive deafness will cause the sound to be louder in the abnormal ear. In this woman, given Rinne\u0027s test is positive bi-laterally it is unlikely that she is suffering from conductive deafness. Weber\u0027s test reveals sound is louder in her right ear suggesting that she has worse \u003Cstrong\u003Esensorineural deafness in her left ear.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensorineural deafness in both ears, worse on the right\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because Weber\u0027s test lateralizes to the right ear, indicating worse hearing in the left ear.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConductive deafness in both ears, worse on the left\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because Rinne\u0027s test is positive bilaterally, ruling out conductive hearing loss.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConductive deafness of right ear, sensorineural deafness on left\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because Rinne\u0027s test is positive in both ears, indicating sensorineural rather than conductive hearing loss.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConductive deafness in both ears, worse on the right\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because Rinne\u0027s test is positive bilaterally, ruling out conductive hearing loss.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Presbycusis is a term used to describe age-related sensorineural hearing loss."],"references":["Gates GA, Mills JH. Presbycusis. Lancet 2005; 366:1111-20."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76127"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"32"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76127"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T08:50:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T08:52:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"32"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"at